        5 comments
    </a>
    
    
    </p>
</div>




<h2>
    <a href="/blog/simulating-the-belousov-zhabotinsky-reaction/">Simulating the Belousov-Zhabotinsky reaction</a>
</h2>




<h6 class="post-meta">
    Posted by:
    
    <a href="/blog/author/christian/">christian</a>
    
    
    
    in
    
    <a href="/blog/category/featured-on-frontpage/">Featured on frontpage</a>
    
    
    
    on 27 Jul 2017
</h6>





<a href="/blog/simulating-the-belousov-zhabotinsky-reaction/">
    <img class="img-thumbnail pull-left" src="/static/media/uploads/blog/bz_reaction/.thumbnails/_img-0082.png/_img-0082-90x90.png">
</a>





<p>The Belousov-Zhabotinsky (BZ) reaction is a classical example of a non-equibrium chemical oscillator in which the components exhibit periodic changes in concentration.</p>




